      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you're dealing with a memory leak in your embedded C++ project, it's a bit like trying to find a hidden, mischievous goblin in a dark forest. You know it's there, but it's playing hide and seek with you. First, you'll need to arm yourself with some tools, like a trusty lantern to light up the path. In this case, your lantern is a memory profiler or a debugger.\n\nStart by casting a wide net with your lantern, scanning through your codebase for any suspicious goblin-like behavior. Look for any dynamic memory allocations using `new` and `delete`, or `malloc` and `free`. These are often the culprits behind memory leaks. Remember, goblins love to hide in the shadows of dynamic memory.\n\nOnce you've identified potential goblin hideouts, it's time to set up traps. In the world of debugging, this means using tools like Valgrind or AddressSanitizer. These tools will help you track down the goblins by monitoring your program's memory usage and reporting any leaks.\n\nAs you hunt down these goblins, keep an eye out for any memory allocations that are not matched with corresponding deallocations. It's like finding a goblin's footprint in the mud – it might",
