      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Implementing a wrapper around your `malloc` calls to record the return address and size for every allocation is a clever idea, and it's a technique often used in embedded systems to track down memory leaks. However, you're right to be concerned about the overhead this might introduce, especially in a real-time system where timing is critical.\n\nTo minimize the impact on your system's performance, consider the following approaches:\n\n1. **Selective Instrumentation**: Instead of wrapping every `malloc` call, selectively instrument only the parts of the code where memory leaks are suspected. This reduces the overhead to just the areas of interest.\n\n2. **Conditional Compilation**: Use conditional compilation to include the wrapper code only in debug builds. This way, you can have the overhead only when you need it, without affecting the release build's performance.\n\n3. **Asynchronous Logging**: If possible, log the allocation information asynchronously to avoid blocking the main control loop. This could involve writing to a buffer and then processing the buffer at a less critical time.\n\n4. **Memory Pooling**: Use memory pooling for frequently allocated and deallocated objects. This can reduce the overhead of individual allocations and deallocations, as well as make it easier to track memory usage.\n\n5",
